        </table-wrap>
        <p><bold>Normal gene product.</bold> The function of seipin, a 398-amino acid residue integral membrane protein of the endoplasmic reticulum (ER), is unknown.</p>
        <p><bold>Abnormal gene product.</bold> The p.Asn88Ser and p.Ser90Leu mutations disrupt the N-glycosylation motif and appear to result in proteins that are improperly folded. Furthermore, mutant proteins abnormally accumulate in the ER and eventual lead to cell death [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="spg17.REF.ito.2007.237">Ito &#x00026; Suzuki 2007</xref>]. The Asn88Ser seipin transgenic mice develop a progressive spastic motor deficit and neurogenic muscular atrophy, recapitulating the phenotype of patients with seipinopathy [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="spg17.REF.yagi.2011.3831">Yagi et al 2011</xref>].</p>
      </sec>
